<DOC><DOCNO> AP880426-0085 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-04-26-88 0840EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r i PM-AsbestosFire     04-26 0226</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Asbestos Fire,0237</SECOND><HEAD>Fire Sweeps NATO Warehouse, Sending Asbestos Into The Air</HEAD><DATELINE>DONNINGTON, England (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   A fire at a NATO storage depot gaveoff a huge cloud of smoke that dusted nearby communities withdangerous asbestos, authorities said.   Officials used bullhorns to warn people living just west ofMonday's fire to stay inside and avoid stirring up the asbestospowder.   The asbestos came from the roof of the burning 10-acre warehouseat the depot in Donnington in western England.   A team of 120 local workers put on masks and protective clothingto clean up the worst contaminated areas.   Asbestos is a fibrous material used to fireproof and insulate.It has been linked to lung cancer and other diseases, and otherbuilding materials have increasingly replaced it.   In dust form, asbestos can cause an often fatal lung diseasecalled pneumoconiosis.   The warehouse that caught fire is part of a North AtlanticTreaty Organization depot employing several thousand people. It isone of the Western defense alliance's biggest storage areas fortechnical equipment and spare parts for military vehicles.   The army said the warehouse contained no ammunition. No cause ofthe fire was given.   The 190 civilian and British army personnel working in thewarehouse were evacuated, and there were no reports of injury.   The Army said damage was expected to run into millions ofdollars.</TEXT></DOC>